qas.question: What does not include characters in the Chinese family?
What is formed by Chinese principles?
What created over 5,000 characters with similar strokes?

context: Even the <a0_0>Zhonghua Zihai<a0_0/> does not include characters in the Chinese family of scripts created to represent non-Chinese languages. <a1_0>Characters<a1_0/> formed by Chinese principles in other languages include the roughly 1,500 Japanese-made kokuji given in the Kokuji no Jiten, the Korean-made gukja, the over 10,000 Sawndip characters still in use in Guangxi, and the almost 20,000 Nôm characters formerly used in Vietnam.[citation needed] More divergent descendents of Chinese script include <a2_0>Tangut script<a2_0/>, which created over 5,000 characters with similar strokes but different formation principles to Chinese characters.
